🔹 Problem: Group Anagrams
Given an array of strings strs, group the anagrams together.

👉 Example:
Input: ["eat","tea","tan","ate","nat","bat"]
Output: [["eat","tea","ate"],["tan","nat"],["bat"]]

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach
💡 Idea:
For every string, compare it with all others and group manually using an anagram check.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n² * k log k)
(n = number of strings, k = length of each string)

Space: O(n)

✅ Code (C++):
bool isAnagram(string a, string b) {
    if(a.size() != b.size()) return false;
    sort(a.begin(), a.end());
    sort(b.begin(), b.end());
    return a == b;
}

vector<vector<string>> groupAnagrams(vector<string>& strs) {
    vector<vector<string>> result;
    vector<bool> visited(strs.size(), false);

    for(int i = 0; i < strs.size(); i++) {
        if(visited[i]) continue;

        vector<string> group;
        group.push_back(strs[i]);
        visited[i] = true;

        for(int j = i + 1; j < strs.size(); j++) {
            if(!visited[j] && isAnagram(strs[i], strs[j])) {
                group.push_back(strs[j]);
                visited[j] = true;
            }
        }

        result.push_back(group);
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Very slow (nested loops + sorting)
Repeated work (same strings sorted many times)
Not scalable

📌 When to use:
Only to explain baseline in interview

⚡ 2. Better Approach (Sorting as Key)
💡 Idea:
Sort each string → use sorted string as a key in hashmap

👉 All anagrams will have the same sorted form

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n * k log k)
Space: O(n * k)

✅ Code:
vector<vector<string>> groupAnagrams(vector<string>& strs) {
    unordered_map<string, vector<string>> mp;

    for(string s : strs) {
        string key = s;
        sort(key.begin(), key.end());
        mp[key].push_back(s);
    }

    vector<vector<string>> result;
    for(auto& it : mp) {
        result.push_back(it.second);
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Sorting every string → costly for large strings
Slightly slower than optimal for big k
Uses extra space for keys

📌 When to use:
Most common interview solution
Easy to implement and explain

🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Frequency Count as Key)
💡 Idea:
Instead of sorting, use character frequency as key

👉 Example:
"eat" → a1e1t1 → "1#0#0#...#1#..." (26-length key)

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n * k)
Space: O(n * k)

✅ Code:
vector<vector<string>> groupAnagrams(vector<string>& strs) {
    unordered_map<string, vector<string>> mp;

    for(string s : strs) {
        vector<int> freq(26, 0);

        for(char c : s) {
            freq[c - 'a']++;
        }

        string key = "";
        for(int count : freq) {
            key += to_string(count) + "#";
        }

        mp[key].push_back(s);
    }

    vector<vector<string>> result;
    for(auto& it : mp) {
        result.push_back(it.second);
    }

    return result;
}

❌ Cons:
Key construction is less intuitive
Only works directly for fixed charset (like lowercase letters)
Slightly more complex to explain

📌 When to use:
When strings are long (avoid sorting cost)
When you want true optimal performance
